Nope, APC just needs to be enabled in your INI so that opcode caching is in effect. Is there any other information that would be useful to help us find out why it appears to be slower on your system? What kind of environment are you on? How are you benchmarking the two session handlers?

I was comparing them yesterday, and with APC enabled, version 2 was _always_ faster than version 1. Here are samples of two scripts I was using to test.

**For SDK version 1:**

``` php
<?php

$time = microtime(true);

require 'aws-sdk-for-php/sdk.class.php';
require 'config-sdk1.php';

$db = new AmazonDynamoDB();
$db->register_session_handler(array(
    'session_locking' => false,
    'table_name'      => 'sessions',
    'hash_key'        => 'id',
));

session_start();
$_SESSION['random_value'] = rand(0, 100);
session_commit();

echo microtime(true) - $time;
```

**For SDK version 2:**

``` php
<?php

$time = microtime(true);

require 'vendor/autoload.php';
$aws = Aws\Common\Aws::factory('config-sdk2.php');

$db = $aws->get('dynamodb');
$db->registerSessionHandler(array(
    'locking_strategy' => null,
    'table_name'       => 'sessions',
    'hash_key'         => 'id',
));

session_start();
$_SESSION['random_value'] = rand(0, 100);
session_commit();

echo microtime(true) - $time;
```

These scripts include the time to bootstrap the SDK, instantiate the DynamoDB client, register the session handler, read from the session, and write to the session. I ran them hundreds and hundreds of times, took averages, etc. I also has some other scripts that measured each part of these scripts in more finer grained steps.

You should also try increasing the apc.shm_size even more than 64MB. The size this setting needs to be depends on the other libraries you're using as well. As an example, many Magento (a large framework) users recommend an apc.shm_size of 256M.

